# ── KitchenHub WebRTC TURN Configuration ──────────────────────────────────
# 
# By default, the system uses STUN-only ICE servers (Google's public STUN).
# This works well for most users but may fail for those behind restrictive
# firewalls or double NATs. Configure TURN servers for global reliability.
#
# ── Option 1: Metered.ca (FREE Tier with 1GB/month) ────────────────────
# Simple, free public TURN service. No auth required for public tier.
# Sign up: https://metered.ca/ → get your credential hash
#
# Example (free tier - no credentials needed):
# VITE_ICE_SERVERS='[
#   { "urls": "stun:stun.l.google.com:19302" },
#   { "urls": "stun:stun1.l.google.com:19302" },
#   { "urls": "turn:stun.metered.ca:3478", "username": "", "credential": "" },
#   { "urls": "turn:stun.metered.ca:3478?transport=tcp", "username": "", "credential": "" }
# ]'
#
# ── Option 2: Self-Hosted coturn (FREE, open-source) ────────────────────
# Deploy on your own VPS (~$5/month on DigitalOcean/Linode/AWS free tier)
# Setup: https://github.com/coturn/coturn
#
# Example:
# VITE_ICE_SERVERS='[
#   { "urls": "stun:stun.l.google.com:19302" },
#   { "urls": "turn:turn.yourdomain.com:3478?transport=udp", "username": "user", "credential": "pass123" },
#   { "urls": "turn:turn.yourdomain.com:3479?transport=tcp", "username": "user", "credential": "pass123" }
# ]'
#
# ── Option 3: Public Relay Services (Community-Run) ──────────────────────
# Various open-source projects maintain free public TURN servers.
# Use with caution (limited bandwidth, potential abuse, no SLA).
#
# Example open relay (no credentials):
# VITE_ICE_SERVERS='[
#   { "urls": "stun:stun.l.google.com:19302" },
#   { "urls": "turn:numb.viagenie.ca", "username": "webrtc@live.com", "credential": "muazkh" }
# ]'
#
# ── Option 4: Premium (Twilio, Xirsys) for Production ──────────────────
# If you need enterprise reliability:
# Twilio: https://www.twilio.com/ ($$, regional redundancy)
# Xirsys: https://xirsys.com/ ($$, simple API-based provisioning)
#
# ── Format Requirements ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The VITE_ICE_SERVERS environment variable must be a valid JSON array.
# Each server object can have:
#   - urls: string or array of URLs (stun: or turn: protocol)
#   - username: optional, required for TURN servers
#   - credential: optional, required for TURN servers
#   - credentialType: optional, "password" (default) or "oauth"
#
# Example complete configuration:
VITE_ICE_SERVERS='[
  { "urls": "stun:stun.l.google.com:19302" },
  { "urls": "stun:stun1.l.google.com:19302" },
  { "urls": "stun:stun2.l.google.com:19302" },
  { "urls": "turn:turn.example.com:3478?transport=udp", "username": "admin", "credential": "secure-password" },
  { "urls": "turn:turn.example.com:3479?transport=tcp", "username": "admin", "credential": "secure-password" }
]'

# ── Testing Your Configuration ────────────────────────────────────────────
# After setting VITE_ICE_SERVERS:
# 1. Rebuild: npm run build (in both admin-dashboard and agent-portal)
# 2. Check browser console for: "[WebRTC] Using custom ICE servers from env"
# 3. Run WebRTC connectivity test (e.g., https://webrtc.github.io/samples/web/content/datachannel/pc1/)
# 4. Full end-to-end test: Admin initiates backstage takeover, verify video streams
#
# If VITE_ICE_SERVERS is not set or invalid, the system falls back to STUN-only.
# This is acceptable for development and internal networks, but production
# deployments (especially those facing the public internet) should always have
# TURN configured.

# ── Deployment Notes ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# - For admin-dashboard: Set VITE_ICE_SERVERS before running npm run build
# - For agent-portal (Electron): Same env var is used by the renderer process
# - For security: Keep TURN credentials private and rotate them regularly
# - For performance: Test with your expected geographic distribution
#   (cloud-deployed TURN in US-East may not be optimal for APAC users)
